premise_source_doc_sentence: The 6th Army began attacks from Arras north to Armentières in late October , which were faced by the BEF III Corps from Rouges Bancs , past Armentières north to the Douve river beyond the Lys .

Brigadier-General J. E. Edmonds , an official historian , wrote in the British History of the Great War , wrote that the II Corps battle at La Bassée could be taken as separate but that the battles from Armentières to Messines and Ypres , were better understood as a battle in two parts , an offensive by III Corps and the Cavalry Corps from against which the Germans retired and an offensive by the German 6th Army and 4th Army from which from 30 October , took place mainly north of the Lys , when the battles of Armentières and Messines merged with the Battles of Ypres .
